Fingerprint Generation

In this task, molecular fingerprints were generated from SMILES representations of compounds using PaDELPy.
These fingerprints encode chemical structures into numerical vectors suitable for machine learning and QSAR modeling.

Input Preparation

The SMILES data was extracted and converted into .smi format required by PaDEL:

data = df[['canonical_smiles', 'molecule_chembl_id']]

data['canonical_smiles'].to_csv(
    "smiles_chembl.smi",
    index=None,
    header=None
)
PubChem Fingerprints
Code
padeldescriptor(
    mol_dir="smiles_chembl.smi",
    d_file="pubchem_fingerprints.csv",
    fingerprints=True,
    retainorder=True
)
Output
File: pubchem_fingerprints.csv
Feature size: 881 bits
Substructure Fingerprints
Code
Substruc_fp = "SubstructureFingerprinter.xml"

padeldescriptor(
    mol_dir="smiles_chembl.smi",
    d_file="Substructure_fingerprints.csv",
    fingerprints=True,
    descriptortypes=Substruc_fp,
    retainorder=True
)
Output
File: Substructure_fingerprints.csv
Feature size: ~307 bits
Why Fingerprints Are Important

Molecular fingerprints transform chemical structures into binary feature vectors, which enables:

Machine learning model training (QSAR)
Chemical similarity comparison
Efficient representation of molecular features
Tool Used
PaDELPy
Reasons for Selection:
Widely used in cheminformatics workflows
Generates standardized and reproducible fingerprints
Supports multiple fingerprint types (PubChem, Substructure)
Easily integrates with Python pipelines
